# Days of Week — Memory Drill

## Purpose

Drill English day → Greek day name and reverse. 7 items, completely arbitrary, must be memorised. Used constantly for scheduling, plans, and past narrative ("last Monday", "on Thursday"). Currently in /learn/essentials as reference only.

Target: 3 seconds.

## The 7 forms

| English | Greek | Notes |
|---------|-------|-------|
| Monday | Δευτέρα (η) | feminine |
| Tuesday | Τρίτη (η) | feminine |
| Wednesday | Τετάρτη (η) | feminine |
| Thursday | Πέμπτη (η) | feminine |
| Friday | Παρασκευή (η) | feminine |
| Saturday | Σάββατο (το) | neuter |
| Sunday | Κυριακή (η) | feminine |

All feminine except Σάββατο (neuter). Worth noting — Saturday is the odd one out.

## In-context forms (teach alongside)

Days are used with `την` (accusative feminine) for "on [day]":
- on Monday = **τη Δευτέρα**
- on Saturday = **το Σάββατο** (neuter accusative)
- on Sunday = **την Κυριακή**

The in-context form is what learners actually produce in sentences. Consider drilling both: bare noun AND "on [day]" phrase.

## Related time expressions (optional extension)

| English | Greek |
|---------|-------|
| yesterday | χτες |
| today | σήμερα |
| tomorrow | αύριο |
| the day after tomorrow | μεθαύριο |
| last week | την περασμένη εβδομάδα |
| next week | την επόμενη εβδομάδα |
| weekend | το Σαββατοκύριακο |

These 7 time adverbs are high-frequency and pure memorisation. Could be a second filter in the same drill ("Days" vs "Time expressions") rather than a separate drill — the set is small enough.

## Drill format

**Forward**: English → type Greek day name
**Reverse**: Greek → English
**Optional in-context mode**: "on Monday" → "τη Δευτέρα"

## Notes

- 7 items drills fast — consider bundling with time expressions (adds 7 more) for a full 14-item session
- Saturday/Sunday distinction is a common source of errors — worth flagging if learner misses Σάββατο gender
- Accent positions matter: Δευτέρα/Τρίτη/Τετάρτη/Πέμπτη — all end in accented -α or -η
